Let's provide guidance.

Great – the health check now says every instance is running, but the data= size of 4 KB tells us that the data directories are empty.
When we re‑ran the v10.5 installer it renamed the old folders to …backup.YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS and then created fresh, empty data/ folders. Your original chats, uploads, vector DB files, and the secret key that ties the UI to those chats are still sitting in those backup directories.

Below is a step‑by‑step rescue plan that will:

Locate the backup folders that were created automatically.
Copy the original data/ contents (your chats, uploaded files, embeddings, etc.) back into the fresh instances.
Restore the original .webui_secret_key so the UI recognises the existing users and remembers the last‑selected model.
Restart the whole stack and verify that the data sizes grow back to their original values.
1️⃣ List the backup folders that the installer created
bash


# Show every folder that ends with ".backup.*"
ls -d ~/testwebui.backup* \
       ~/openwebui2ver7.backup* \
       ~/openwebui3.backup* \
       ~/testwebui-v10.backup* \
       ~/openwebui2ver7-v10.backup* \
       ~/openwebui4.backup* 2>/dev/null
You should see something like:



/home/devoshireroad777/openwebui2ver7.backup.20260612_015130
/home/devoshireroad777/openwebui2ver7.backup.20260612_021501
/home/devoshireroad777/openwebui3.backup.20260612_021600
/home/devoshireroad777/testwebui.backup.20260612_030004
...
If you see none of these folders, the backup may have been removed after the reinstall – in that case the original data is unfortunately gone. Let me know if that’s the case and we’ll discuss what can still be salvaged (e.g. exported chat files you may have saved).

2️⃣ Restore the data directories and the secret‑key files
Run the block below exactly as shown. It will:

Pick the most recent backup for each instance (the one with the highest timestamp).
Delete the empty data/ directory that the installer created.
Copy the backed‑up data/ directory back in place.
Replace the freshly‑generated .webui_secret_key with the original one (so existing users stay logged in and the UI remembers the model you last chose).
bash

#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
umask 077

# List of the six instance names (folder names in $HOME)
INSTANCES=(
    "testwebui"
    "openwebui2ver7"
    "openwebui3"
    "testwebui-v10"
    "openwebui2ver7-v10"
    "openwebui4"
)

for NAME in "${INSTANCES[@]}"; do
    echo "🔧 Restoring $NAME …"

    # Find the newest backup folder for this instance
    BACKUP=$(ls -dt "${HOME}/${NAME}.backup"* 2>/dev/null | head -n 1 || true)

    if [[ -z "$BACKUP" ]]; then
        echo "   ⚠️  No backup found for $NAME – skipping."
        continue
    fi

    # 1️⃣ Replace the secret key (if it exists in the backup)
    if [[ -f "${BACKUP}/.webui_secret_key" ]]; then
        cp -a "${BACKUP}/.webui_secret_key" "${HOME}/${NAME}/"
        echo "   ✅ Restored .webui_secret_key"
    else
        echo "   ⚠️  No .webui_secret_key in backup – keeping the new one (you may be logged out)."
    fi

    # 2️⃣ Restore the data folder
    if [[ -d "${BACKUP}/data" ]]; then
        # Remove the empty data folder the installer created
        rm -rf "${HOME}/${NAME}/data"
        # Copy the full backup data directory
        cp -a "${BACKUP}/data" "${HOME}/${NAME}/"
        echo "   ✅ Restored data directory (chat history, uploads, vectors, …)"
    else
        echo "   ⚠️  No data folder in backup – nothing to copy."
    fi

    # Ensure correct permissions (same as the installer expects)
    chmod -R 700 "${HOME}/${NAME}/data"
    chmod 600 "${HOME}/${NAME}/.webui_secret_key" 2>/dev/null || true
done

echo "✅ All restorations finished."
Copy‑paste the entire block into your terminal (press Enter after the final "). It will run automatically.

